    "url": "https://www.linkedin.com/posts/jeffevans_most-founders-fail-because-their-vision-is-activity-7438241222512537601-eOKe?utm_source=combined_share_message&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAACKcI8YBZXZpYrQ5Sh_n3WjQ4z9yqmCEvUo",
    "timeSincePosted": "1d",
    "shareUrn": "urn:li:share:7438183428883337216",
    "text": "Most founders fail because their vision is too clear.\n\nMy biggest lesson \u2013 when your ICP screams, pivot. Immediately.\n\n\"Just connect us with brands.\"\nHeard that for months. Kept shipping tools anyway.\n\nOne call sticks with me. A podcast host with maybe 15,000 listeners, growing fast. She told me: \"Just connect me with a sponsor for next season. That's all I need.\"\n\nI nodded, took notes. Though, well, they aren\u2019t our ICP. \n\nI think founders really struggle to find enough supporting data points to build conviction to switch quickly. What\u2019s nuts is people you\u2019re contacting still booked follow up meetings baiting us on to think we were in the right space. Anyone that tells you they are interested but won\u2019t buy in the next 3 months is your biggest company risk. \n\nYou hear the feedback and log it. Usually this feedback is pointing to a COMPLETELY different business. Changing isn\u2019t just a quick prototype away. It\u2019s convincing everyone involved and yourself that your first insight and vision isn\u2019t that good. And you have limited data to prove that you\u2019re wrong.\u00a0 \n\nWorst part is we\u2019ve all read the Mom Test, we know the drill.\n\nWe lost probably 12 months to \u201cnot being able to drop our initial vision\u201d. Even after hearing this more and more, we still weren't sure if we were wrong with our initial vision. And that place is the danger zone. Where companies waste a ton of runway.\n\nUsually you're not looking for proof that you're wrong. You're looking for: \u201cis it really taking off?\u201d\n\nYou gotta look for a big shift. Hard truth is most of us haven\u2019t hit that - and we delay by believing certain conditions are met to \u2018truly test\u2019 it.\n\nWhen we finally started connecting them with brand partners, the response was almost embarrassing. Like we'd been hoarding the answer in a drawer the whole time.\n\nI\u2019m still wondering how many other signals I'm filtering out right now.",
